###############################################################################
#
#   Ce Regression test plan  "%Z% %M% %I% - %G% %U% AG CS Phoenix"
#   Test Type Legend:  S  - Search and Substitute
#                      C  - Cursor Placement
#                      D  - Drawing / Highlighting / Mouse Dropping
#                      V  - VT100 emulation
#                      P  - Cmd Parsing & Option Processing
#                      O  - Other (Misc.)
#                      U  - Undo Redo
#                      E  - Event Processing
#                      M  - Data Manipulation
#                      X  - Copy, Paste, Region, and Color

    ************************************** R2.6.2 *****************************************
    ************************************** R2.6.2 *****************************************
    ************************************** R2.6.2 *****************************************
    In Ce (Type E)
    Open a window on a new file.  Type some junk.  Then use the exit button to
    log off.  Log back on.  The file should have been saved or at least saved 
    as a crash file.  Make sure this works on both Solaris and Linux.

    In Ce (Type D)
    Browse a file with -bell visual and try to type in the main window.  The
    DM output window should flash.  Use -bell VISUAL and repeat, the main 
    window should flash.  Use -bell on and the terminal should beep (assuming
    there is a speaker hooked up.)  Use -bell off and no flash or beep should
    occur.  One of these is the default in your .Xdefaults.

    ************************************** R2.6.1 *****************************************
    ************************************** R2.6.1 *****************************************
    ************************************** R2.6.1 *****************************************
    In Ceterm (Type O)
    Make sure ^c is defined as 
    kd ^c cntlc -h 03  PRIMARY ke
    Start a long ls and use ^c to interupt it.  Then mark a region of text
    and use ^c to copy it.  Paste it somewhere to see that it was copied.

    ************************************** R2.6 *******************************************
    ************************************** R2.6 *******************************************
    ************************************** R2.6 *******************************************
    In Ce: (Type X)
    Label a line:  lbl bbb
    Turn on lineno so you see the label
    break the line with en both before and after the label.
    The label should stay with the text.

    In Ce: (Type X)
    Color a line.
    Type before the colored area in insert mode.  The colored area should move.
    Type before the colored area in overstrike mode.  The colored area should not move.

    ************************************** R2.5.5 ****************************************
    ************************************** R2.5.5 ****************************************
    ************************************** R2.5.5 ****************************************
    In Ceterm: (Type C)
    Start typing in the UNIX command window.  Type a bit then type 321 (Escape key)
    to move you to the "Command:" prompt.  Use the arrow up key (au) to move back to
    the UNIX line and the press the End key (tr).

    In Ce: (Type C)
    In a file with more than one screen of data, press ^b.  Type on the last line.  Include
    the string 321 'Escape Key' which moves to the Command: prompt.  Use the arrow key (au)
    to get back into the main window and press the end key (tr).  Make sure the cursor goes
    to the end of the line.


    In Ceterm: (Type C)
    Create shell script /tmp/zz containing a long string. 
    Line below will create shell script
    echo 'echo "addddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddddd\c"' > /tmp/zz
    Start a ceterm in the np 7 postion (upper left corner)
    pwd
    sh /tmp/zz
    Cursor should not fly out of the window.
    exit
    Cursor should not fly out of the window.

    In Ceterm: (Type M)
    Start a ceterm with   ceterm -cmd "pn -r /tmp/z1"
    Do an ls -la
    Close the window using the window manager.
    Make sure the file /tmp/z1 contains the transcript pad.

    ************************************** R2.5.4 ****************************************
    ************************************** R2.5.4 ****************************************
    ************************************** R2.5.4 ****************************************
    In Ceterm: (Type X)
    With: kd ^4 tmw;pb;tb;tl;ca yellow ke
    Start a ceterm and do an ls -la to fill the screen.
    Press ^4, the last line of text should be highighted and the cursor should
    return to the unix prompt.
    do another ls -la.  Put the cursor in the main window and scroll back a bit.
    Press ^4.  The cursor should not appear to move.  Scrolling down should show the
    last line has been colored.  This tests the sl and rl commands.

    In Ce: (Type X)
    In a ce started from a UNIX shell, so stderr goes to the pad.
    With: kd ^4 tmw;pb;tb;tl;ca yellow ke
    create_data 10 400 > /tmp/z123
    ce /tmp/z123
    Press ^4
    Go up to the line of t's and press Esc.
    ! create_data 8 132000
    run the command debug color
    make sure there are no errors about bits being wrong.  debug colorbits adds more info.
    
    In Ceterm: (Type C)
    In a ce started from a UNIX shell, so stderr goes to the pad.
    With: kd ^3 sl;tmw;pb;tb;tl;ca red;rl ke
    in a reasonably large dir like crpad, do la -la.
    Leave the cursor on the input line and press ^3.  The last line should color to red
    and the cursor should not move.  Do another ls -la.  Move the cursor to the
    middle of the screen and press ^3.  The last line should color red and the
    cursor not move.  Do another ls -la.  Scroll back a page or so.  Press ^3 and
    nothing should appear to happen.  Scrolling down should show the colored line.

    In Ceterm: (type X)
    run from UNIX:
    echo "\002\002sl;tmw;pb;tb;tl;ca blue;rl"
    The echo of the command should be blue.  The cursor should remain
    in the UNIX window.


    In Ceterm: (Type D)
    On Linux, resize the window using the window manager handles, make sure 
    1.  The ce window does not snap to a small size.
    2.  You do not get a bunch of prompts stacking up on the command line.

    In Ceterm: (Type P)
    On Linux, make sure cp brings up a live ceterm window.

    ************************************** R2.5.3 ****************************************
    ************************************** R2.5.3 ****************************************
    ************************************** R2.5.3 ****************************************

    In Ceterm: (Type O)
    Make sure linux goes into dot mode correctly for rlogin, su, telnet, and
    ftp.

    In Ceterm: (Type P)
    Run ceterm -cmd init.cmdf
    Where init.cmdf contains
    pn;tdmo;tl;dr;tr;xl -l name "title '";xc -a -l name;cmdf -p name;msg '';tmw
    Run a pwd or so and then execute exit.  Make sure the title changes to
    <STDIN>.

    ************************************** R2.5.2 ****************************************
    ************************************** R2.5.2 ****************************************
    ************************************** R2.5.2 ****************************************

    In Ce: (Type O)
    Open a window displaying back to a windows machine running Hummingbird Exceed.
    In this newly opened window run the commands:
    geo 500x500+100+100
    geo 350x350-100-100
    One at a time.  Then slide the window using the title bar so the 
    "Command:" prompt is off the bottom the screen.  Then press escape to move
    the window back on screen.  The bug was exceed would crash after any geo command.
    Make sure the pulldown menu's and scrollbars are visible.

    In Ceterm: (Type D)
    Turn on recording, (rec -p cemacro) and make sure the lower case r box
    comes on.  Then turn recording off (rec) and make sure the box turns off.
    Turn scroll mode (ws) on and off make sure the S box and J box toggle.
    Turn overstride mode on and off (ei) and make sure the I box and O box
    toggle back and forth.

    ************************************** R2.5.1 ****************************************
