    that the cursor jumps back when the "loaded 10,000 lines" message
    came out.                                              


    In ceterm (Type O) (Failed at 2.5.2)
    type $ su
    and type a passwd backspace over it, and type it again.
    you can now undo it and see it.



    In ce (Type D)
    In a file that has 75,000 lines
    Mark line 2; go to line 74998 and "ca green blue;sb -off".
    go 24000  mark - go 26000 leave pad to the right;
    go back in Make sure highlight is correct.


    In ce (Type E)
    Activate a pulldown with m1.  Drag off the bottom and release.
    Move back into the menu bar and press m1.  Make sure the
    menu appears.


    In ce (Type D)
    Put window in NP3 position.
    Do ^t
    Put window in NP5 position.
    Make sure there is no mouse dropping.


    in Ceterm (Type D)
    execute a command like pathlook 'xmk*'
    As soon as the first line appears, before the prompt returns,
    goto the main window and start moving the cursor.  When the
    prompt appears make sure a mouse dropping is not generated.
    Sometimes this takes two or three times to reproduce.


    In Ce (Type S)
    Define:  kd ^r // ke  # This is the default
             kd ^e so ke  # Repeat substitute (also the default)
    Over the following data:
    Col 1
    |
    V
    This is an ABC test ABC test abc
    more of ABC ABC
    Put the cursor on the first line and run:
    so /ABC/DEF/
    This will change the first occuance.  Then press ^r.
    It should find the next abc.  Error was that ce reports that
    it cannot find ABC in the rest of the file.  Note that this only
    happens with upper case.  Lower case is ok.  Also if case sensitivity
    is on, it works ok.  Thus to demonstrate the error you must be in
    the default (sc -off) mode.


    in Ce (Type P)
    Test the following subsitute commands.
    so/#//
    so/;//


    in Ceterm (Type V)
    Go into vt mode.  Edit a file with the following data with vi.
    ^d down a page.  arrow down to the line starting
    with a #.  Arrow right.  The wrong data gets written out.
    Col 1
    | 
    V
    date=`/bin/date "+%a %h %d, 19%y  %r"`
    
    if [ "$PASSWORD_EXPIRES" -le 7 -a "$PASSWORD_EXPIRES" -ge 5 ]
    then
       print "\nPassword expires in "$PASSWORD_EXPIRES" days.\n"
    fi
    
    if [ "$PASSWORD_EXPIRES" -le 4 -a "$PASSWORD_EXPIRES" -ge 2 ]
    then
       print "\nPassword expires in >>> "$PASSWORD_EXPIRES" <<< days!\n"
    fi
    
    if [ "$PASSWORD_EXPIRES" -eq 1 ]
    then
       /usr/bin/X11/xdialog -title Password "Your Password expires tomorrow, better change it now!!!"
    fi
    
    # set -o allexport noclobber
    set +o nounset
    
    FCEDIT=pad
    
    # Other standard environment variables
    export ENV=$HOME/.kshrc
    export FPATH=$HOME/flib
    export VISUAL='/phx/bin/ce -w -font fixed -cmd "[0,0]ww -c 72;tl;en;au"'
    export HISTORY=100
    export CDPATH=.:$HOME:/:..   
    #export CDPATH=.:..:$HOME
    export PS1="$LOGNAME:=> "  
    export PS2='More: '
    export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/usr/openwin/lib:/phx/lib:/lib:/usr/openwin:/pkg/softbench/lib/SB4.0:/usr/ucblib
    #export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/usr/dt/lib:/usr/openwin/lib:/phx/lib:/lib
    export OPENWINHOME=/usr/openwin
    export HISTSIZE=1000
    export MAIL=/home/yountm/Mail/Mailbox
    export MAILPATH="/sys5/usr/mail/$LOGNAME%You have mail."
    export MAILCHECK=60000
    export MAILER=~/bin/elm
