    in Ce (Type O)
    set tabstop to  ts 25 5 -r
    Error was that this put ce into an infinite loop


    In ce (Type E)
    rm /usr/tmp/file
    ce /usr/tmp/file
    debug cclist    
    Look at the cclist, it should have a made up inode, the
    create date should be the The directory inode, and the
    size should be zero.
    From a UNIX window, ce /usr/tmp/file, the cc should be
    recognized. Telnet to another machine, ce /usr/tmp/file, the
    cc should not be recognized. Close the other node window.
    Type a few characters in /usr/tmp/file and save it.
    debug cclist
    There should be real inode, create date, and size information.
    Run ce /usr/tmp/file, the cc should be recognized.
    Close the cc window.
    Add some more characters and save.
    debug cclist
    The cclist should have a new inode.  The create date may
    have changed, The new size should be shown.
    Add some more characters and save.
    debug cclist
    The cclist should have the same inode as last time.
    ce /usr/tmp/file.  The cc should be recognized.
    

    In ce (Type P)
    In the enclosing ceterm window:
        ceopt="-cmd '$'"
        cv $ceopt ~/.profile
        (Go to top of file in first window)
        cv $ceopt ~/.profile
    Make sure the second window comes up and goes to the bottom.
    Use debug @4 to make sure the cc window message parses ok.

    In Ceterm (Type C & D)
    create a long prompt  PS1='ddddddddddddddddddddddddddd'
    Make the window so 1/2 character fits past the prompt.
    Bug was you could position the cursor so it does not shift when you
    type and the letters assemble in the window backwards.

    In ce (Type X)
    In file crpad.c with lineno on.
    Copy the following into the default paste buffer and use cmdf -p
    Make sure it creates both labels.
    lbl                 # create a label at the current position
    1                   # Go to line 1 column 1
    /main *(/;lbl main  # Find the main procedure and set label
    /static void dump_atom/;lbl dump_atom   # find routine dump_atomand set label
    glb                 # Go back where we started


    In ce (Type X)
    Set some labels with lbl and some colored areas.  Make sure that
    one of the colored areas overlaps a label.  Try 1,$dlb and make
    sure the labels go away, but the color is ok.  Then use undo to
    bring back the labels and try 1,$ca to get rid of the color and
    leave the labels.  Make sure the color overlapping the label goes
    away correctly.

    In Ce (Type X)
    Over the following C code:
    Do a rectangular mark starting just past the "  on the last
    printf line and extending UP to the 8 on the first printf line.
    This way the [ is included in the marked region.
    Press escape and execute the command: s/  *\[/='%./
    It should work went you mark from bottom left to top right
    and also for top left to bottom right.
    printf("loadid                   [8];   /* c */
    printf("module                   [31];  /* c */
    printf("storage_name             [8];   /* c */
    printf("whole_iss                [2];   /* c */
    printf("common_loadid            [8];   /* c */
    printf("current_base_id          [12];  /* c */
    printf("old_sccs_id_or_ptiss     [12];  /* c */
    printf("last_user_mod            [7];   /* c */
    printf("domestic_transfer_mod    [1];   /* c */
    printf("partial_uncid_this_load  [1];   /* c */
    printf("no_longname              [1];   /* c */
    printf("exterior                 [1];   /* cl*/
    printf("processor_code           [1];   /* cl*/
    printf("lang_type                [1];   /* cl*/
    printf("remote_owner             [1];   /* c */
    printf("remote_site              [1];   /* c */

    printf("target_id                [8];   /* c */


    In ce (Type P)
    Turn on record.
